post_text: We are very proud of Brant O'Connor.
shared_text:
The Team Roping Journal Magazine is at Will Rogers Memorial Center & Facilities.
Yesterday at 7:16 AM · Fort Worth, TX ·

Brandt O’Connor and Trigger Hargrove were the last champions to be crowned on day 3 at the USTRC National Finals XXXI presented by Cinch. They picked up a total of $47,900 after roping four head in 33.20 seconds to win the #10.5 Shootout!

Keep checking back for more updates brought to you by Resistol.

There’s still more champions to be crowned at the USTRC National Finals presented by CINCH JEANS.

post_text:
Starting Tuesday September 8th, Blair School students will receive free breakfast and free lunch, regardless of their previously determined pay status. This waiver was issued to our state by the USDA and is said to last until December 31, 2020 OR “until funding runs out”. For students who do not take a tray but want a milk or want to purchase an extra milk, the cost for that is still 25 cents.

We highly encourage you to still fill out and turn in your Free and Reduced lunch applications. We will need those to determine your pay status for January, and also, that information is used to help our school and community. Unpaid meal charges will still be collected, so please get those turned in as soon as possible.

post_text: Thomas G Tutten III (Rhett) is the son of Dusty and Heather Tutten. He has attend Blair School for 14 years. Rhett has been active in basketball and FFA. His favorite memories are draining buzzer-beater three-pointers on the basketball courts. Pistols Firing! Rhett’s advice to younger students is to live life to the fullest and to dance every moment you can! Rhett is so thankful to be blessed with the many, many friends he has made through the years. Rhett’s plans are to raise cattle on the family farm with his sister, Ali Jo and nephew, Ridge Mcrae.

The 2020 Graduation Parade will begin at 6:30 on Tuesday, May 12 from the circle drive at Blair School. Seniors will be in cars with their parents in alphabetical order. Students and parents are encouraged to decorate cars however they choose to celebrate their Senior. The parade will make its way through all streets of Blair. We would like to encourage our patrons to honor our seniors by making signs, being in your yards, and having any cards or gifts ready to hand to the seniors as the pass by in the parade.
The parade will conclude at the city park where students will receive diplomas from Mr. Smith and the Board of Education. We would like to ask that the park be… More

post_text: Keely Ortega is the daughter of Adolfo Ortega and Kasey Summer. Also, she is the stepdaughter of her wonderful step-mother, Miranda Ortega and her great step-father, Joe Summers. While in school, she was a member of BETA, and she attended the Southwest Technology Center for Health Science. Keely’s favorite high school memory would have to be going to lunch everyday with her good friends. Her advice for the younger students is that being lazy is stressful, so just show up for school. After she graduates, Keely’s future plans are to work in the Mangum hospital as a CNA while attending Western Oklahoma State College to get her associate’s degree in nursing, and then she plans to continue her education at Cameron University.

Her favorite high school memory is probably almost every high school basketball game. From cheering in the stands with her friends to the weird concession stand pickles, She loved every minute of it. Her advice to the younger students is to always be yourself and never change for anyone. Just be you and have fun in high school. It goes by quicker than you think. Taylor’s future plans are to attend Western Oklahoma State College for 2 years and then further her education at Southwestern Oklahoma State University.

post_text: Mayson Love Crow is the daughter of George Crow and Stana Powell. Her favorite memories are the ones spent with her friends, like when Ally was cast as the grinch in their sock puppet play, and she had to read in a horrendous voice. Also, when a frog rode all the way back from the Ag Barn on top of her car, and the frog eventually went to live in someone’s office. Mayson’s advice to younger students would be to have as much fun as you can while you're in school. Make as many memories as you can and participate in as much as you can. "Looking cool" isn't fun. Being in the middle of the gym acting a fool with your friends is fun, and you'll never get another chance at it. Her future plans are to attend Western Oklahoma State College for two years and then proceed on to either Cameron or SWOSU in pursuit of a degree in psychology, specializing in PTSD.

post_text: Ally Angelly is the daughter of Melvin and Stephanie Angelly. She has attended Blair School for 14 years. While in school, Ally has been active in FFA, 4-H, Student Council, and BETA. Ally's favorite high school memory was dressing up for homecoming spirit week each year. Ally's advice to younger students is to make the most of every moment and be involved in as many activities as you can. For example, be in all of the clubs, enter all of the contests, and take advantage of everything that your school has to offer. Ally will be attending Western Oklahoma State College in the fall. She has already signed with WOSC to be a member of their shooting sports team. While at WOSC, she will be studying Animal Science. After completing her degree at WOSC, she plans on attending Oklahoma State University. Ally’s future plan is to work in the beef cattle industry after completing college.

The Blair Board of Education would like to announce that Seat 3 and 4 have been vacated. Anyone interested in filling this position by appointment, should contact one the following Board Members:
Brandi Boley, brandi.boley@blairschool.org; Brandie Combs, brandie.combs@blairschool.org; Tara Turner, taraturner@blairschool.org; or Superintendent, Mr. Jimmy Smith at (580) 563-2632 or jsmith@blairschool.org so your name can be put on the list of consideration by the next Board meeting on May 12, 2020. You must be a registered voter within the Blair School District to be considered.

Western Oklahoma State College
March 17 at 4:06 PM ·

To ensure the health and safety of Western Oklahoma State College students, faculty, and staff, administration has created a new schedule for the upcoming weeks:

March 16 – March 27: Campus closed to students for spring break.

March 23: All healthy staff, faculty and administrators report and campus operations resume.

March 23 – March 27: Western faculty will transition all classes to virtual delivery.

March 30: All Western classes resume in a virtual delivery format for an initial period of two weeks.

All on and off campus activities and events are suspended until April 6, 2020.
